{"id":22563,"date":"2017-12-08T21:20:18","date_gmt":"2017-12-09T05:20:18","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/?p=22563"},"modified":"2022-02-09T21:44:00","modified_gmt":"2022-02-10T05:44:00","slug":"laurent-series","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"/\/math\/calculus\/laurent-series-22563","title":{"rendered":"Laurent series"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>\r\n    \\(\\)Explains the Laurent series, a representation of a complex function f(z). Named after Pierre Alphonse Laurent, a French mathematician and Military Officer, published in the series 1843. \r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    Unlike the Taylor series which expresses \\(f(z)\\) as a series of terms with non-negative powers of \\(z\\), a Laurent series includes terms with negative powers. Therefore, a Laurent series may be used in cases where a Taylor expansion is not possible.\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container math\">\r\n        $$\r\n            f(z)=\\sum _{n=-\\infty }^{\\infty }a_{n}(z-c)^{n}\r\n        $$\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    where the \\(a_n\\) and \\(c\\) are constants defined by\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"flex-container math\">\r\n        $$\r\n            a_{n}={\\frac {1}{2\\pi i}}\\oint _C{\\frac {f(z)\\,\\mathrm {d} z}{(z-c)^{n+1}}}\r\n        $$\r\n    <\/div>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    The contour \\(C\\) is counterclockwise around a closed, enclosing \\(c\\) and lying in an annulus \\(A\\) in which \\(f(z)\\) analytic. \r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    To calculate, use the <a href=\"\/math\/calculus\/geometric-series-21183#geoseries\">standard<\/a> and <a href=\"\/math\/calculus\/geometric-series-21183#modifiedgeoseries\">modified geometric series<\/a>\r\n    <blockquote>\r\n        $$\r\n            \\frac{1}{1-z}=\r\n            \\left\\{\r\n            \\begin{align}\r\n            \\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}&#038;\\ z^n,&#038;&#038;|z|\\lt1\\nonumber\\\\\r\n            -\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty}&#038;\\ z^{-n},&#038;&#038;|z|\\gt1\\nonumber\r\n            \\end{align}\\nonumber\r\n            \\right.\\nonumber\r\n        $$\r\n    <\/blockquote>\r\n<\/p>\r\n<p>\r\n    Here \\(f(z)=\\frac{1}{1-z}\\) is analytic everywhere apart from the singularity at \\(z=1\\).  Above are the expansions for \\(f(z)\\) in the regions inside and outside the unit circle, centered on \\(z=0\\), where \\(|z|\\lt1\\) is the region inside the circle and \\(|z|\\gt1\\) is the region outside the circle.\r\n<\/p>\r\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"Unlike the Taylor series which expresses <em>f(z)<\/em> as a series of terms with non-negative powers of <em>z<\/em>, a Laurent series includes terms with negative powers. Therefore, a Laurent series may be used in cases where a Taylor expansion is not possible.","protected":false},"author":41,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"inline_featured_image":false,"_mi_skip_tracking":false},"categories":[403],"tags":[],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v18.6 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>Laurent series - Coert Vonk<\/title>\n<meta name=\"description\" content=\"Explains the Laurent series, a representation of a complex function f(z).\" \/>\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1\" \/>\n<link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/math\/calculus\/laurent-series-22563\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:locale\" content=\"en_US\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Laurent series - Coert Vonk\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Explains the Laurent series, a representation of a complex function f(z).\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:url\" content=\"https:\/\/coert.vonk.one\/math\/calculus\/laurent-series-22563\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:site_name\" content=\"Coert Vonk\" \/>\n<meta property=\"article:published_time\" content=\"2017-12-09T05:2